Predicting Fuel Efficiency of Cars (20 marks)

The US Environmental Protection Agency lists different estimates of the fuel economy (FE, in mpg) of passenger cars and trucks sold in the US. For each vehicle, various characteristics are recorded, such as the engine displacement or the number of cylinders. Your task, as a vacation student at the EPA, is to construct a linear regression model for fuel efficiency using data from 2010 (Cars2010) and then use it to predict fuel efficiency of cars in the 2011 model year (Cars2011). These data frames are contained in the file STAT1003Test2.RData.

# Load the data here
print(load("STAT1003Test2.RData"))
[1] "Cars2010" "Cars2011"
  1. Produce two plots that you might use to explore the dataset, but before you do, make sure you understand the structure of the data. Comment on any patterns you see in the plots you have produced. (5 marks)

As part of any exploratory data analysis, it’s always useful to get to know the data, starting with knowing what variables are included in the dataset, to numerical and then graphical summaries. Below, I do this for the data frame Cars2010 (the training set) only, but it would be essential to do this with the test set (Cars2011) as well.

Summary: All the variables are numeric, but some of them occur at discrete levels only.

Plots that it would be useful to produce include a plotting the results of the ‘describe’ function above (though it doesn’t show all the variables), a ‘pairs’ plot (though as we’ll see below, it can be difficult to interpret with this many variables), plots of FE against each of the other variables, and so on.

# Plot 1
plot(describe(Cars2010))
$Categorical


$Continuous

# Plot 2
pairs(Cars2010)

# Plot 3
plot(FE ~ ., data = Cars2010)

# Given that some of the variables occur at discrete levels, we could even
# produce boxplots of FE against these variables instead, e.g.,
boxplot(FE ~ TransLockup, data = Cars2010)

boxplot(FE ~ TransCreeperGear, data = Cars2010)

boxplot(FE ~ IntakeValvePerCyl, data = Cars2010)

boxplot(FE ~ ExhaustValvesPerCyl, data = Cars2010)

boxplot(FE ~ VarValveTiming, data = Cars2010)

boxplot(FE ~ VarValveLift, data = Cars2010)

Comments: Not surprisingly, FE has a negative relationship with engine displacement and the number of cylinders, and this relationship appears slightly curvilinear. The other explanatory variables are either discrete or categorical with two levels, so it is difficult to tell whether strong relationships exist. Boxplots show small differences between mean levels.

  1. Naively, your manager suggests that you eliminate some variables based on their \(p\)-values in the summary output in b. and on your exploratory plots. Based on these naive criteria, which variables do you think ought to be retained in or eliminated from the model? Re-fit the model with only those variables you have decided to retain. (If you do not know how to do that, push ahead with the full model.) (4 marks)

Answer: Choosing variables based only on \(p\)-values, which admittedly is not the best strategy, might lead us to eliminate - using a cutoff of \(0.05\) - NumGears, TransCreeperGear, IntakeValvePerCyl, ExhaustValvesPerCyl, and perhaps VarValveLift as well. The resulting linear model contains relatively few variables:

# There are lots of ways of fitting the smaller model, but one way is to use
# the function 'update' to update a model that has already been created:
lmsmall <- update(lmall, formula. = . ~ . - Numgears - TransCreeperGear - IntakeValvePerCyl - 
    ExhaustValvesPerCyl - VarValveLift)
summary(lmsmall)

lm(formula = FE ~ EngDispl + NumCyl + NumGears + TransLockup + 
    VarValveTiming, data = Cars2010)

  1. Output the ‘standard’ linear model diagnostics that R produces for the reduced model (or full model if you weren’t able to produce one in c.), and comment briefly on any patterns you see in the first three plots that might either support or throw into doubt the validity of a linear model for fuel efficiency. (4 marks)
# Diagnostic plots
plot(lmsmall)

Comment: In this unit, we’ve only learned how to interpret the first three of these plots. The first plot shows some curvature, so we might be missing a squared term in one of the predictors; in the \(q-q\) plot, the standardized residuals show some departure from Normality (plotting a histogram would also reinforce this); and in the third plot, there is some (slight) evidence that variability increases. All in all, we would search for an alternative model to the one fitted here.

  1. Regardless of your comments and analysis in d., your boss wants you to produce predictions of fuel efficiency for 2011 model-year vehicles. Calculate those predictions, produce an appropriate plot comparing predictions and actual values, and calculate the RMSEP. You do not have to put the value of RMSEP on the plot. Comment on any patterns you see in your plot. (5 marks)
# Calculate predictions
FEpred <- predict(lmsmall, newdata = Cars2011)
# Calculate RMSEP
RMSEP <- sqrt(sum((FEpred - Cars2011$FE)^2)/length(FEpred))
RMSEP
[1] 5.019626
# Appropriate plot
Range <- range(c(Cars2011$FE, FEpred))
par(pty = "s")
plot(Cars2011$FE ~ FEpred, xlab = "predicted fuel efficiency", ylab = "actual fuel efficiency", 
    xlim = Range, ylim = Range)
abline(0, 1)
# Not required
text(min(Range), max(Range) - 5, paste("RMSEP: ", round(RMSEP, 2)), adj = 0)

Comments: The curvature we saw in the diagnostic plot above manifests itself here in the plot of actual fuel efficiency for 2011 vehicles against the corresponding predicted value.
